rComments: He obviously has a passion for geology BUT hes not a great lecturer. Most of his lectures were spent exploring Google Earth even tho it wasnt testable material. His tests were very specific and asked about stuff he barely touched in class. I was running an A+ with the other prof but his part of the class dropped it to an A!
Maybe if he spent less time playing around on google earth during class wasting time and more time on his lecture notes and slides he would actually be a decent prof.

He has a bad rep on here... but take it with a grain of salt. He is a very smart man & is obviously passionate about the topics he teaches. He tells lots of personal stories and keeps the lectures interesting and engaging. The content itself is not too difficult. He is also always willing to answer questions and provide clarification.

He means well and clearly enjoys geology, but save yourself the time and just make your notes on the slides (all the info is there) instead of listening to what he says, because he rambles and tells unrelated stories and then will run out of time, and you'll be left to do the notes on your own time. Take Pia if you can

Dr Clark is a really nice guy and was entertaining during class but he doesn't teach class very well and he's more on story telling and facts that doesn't show up on the tests. The tests was tough. Plus, he doesn't finished the slides and the class lectures was not organized well. Plus, we didn't have any questions to practice before the test.

A poor lecturer, he seems to forget what is in his slides which leads to unfinished slideshows that he never goes back to but are still testable. Walks in circles around questions and test questions are tricky and detailed. Would not recommend, his half of GEO1111 made me hate this course. However, content is self teachable.

His lectures are super slow, multiple spelling errors, and half the time I'm not sure if he knows what he's talking about. Ask him a question? Never a straightforward response. Errors in the midterm marking all the time, answers emails late, dodges your question/doesn't understand. Avoid at all cost. Expects you to know so much for an intro course

Ian is alright as a prof, he really knows what he's talking about however you really have to listen and take notes in class because his slideshows aren't sufficient study material. The lab field trips are pretty fun but some of the reports are a lot of work. My biggest issue is that he doesn't believe humans are responsible for climate change!

Dr. Clark is a great guy, super charismatic and there to help you if you need it (if he shows up lol) - love the man as a person. But I just could not grasp his teaching style AT all; lots of rambling and no clear grading schemes. Labs are a mess. You definitely need GEO1115 as a prerequisite for the class even though it's not a requirement.
Cut the bs on labs and get to the point or you're wasting your time. Interesting lectures but not pertinent.

I took this class last year and it was a mess! Labs are long (12 questions and more...) and the prof is not very helpful! He talks a lot and deviate from the main subject! Obviously, you will have to search hours on internet and see many times TA to get answer for the labs! Not recommanded...
teacherRatingTags: ['So many papers', 'Tough grader', 'Get ready to read']

rComments: Really good professor. Makes class and labs interesting.
HE IS SOOOOOOO HOT...  That is why i went to class.  I even wrote that on my course evalutation.  There was NOTHING cold about my quaternary geology course!
Very good prof- just doesn't have a lot of extra time- so hard to get him after classes
